ADPKD - polycystic kidney disease

Autosomal dominant. Patients present in family groups.üòäüòî
It's a common disease (1/1000) incidence.
Commonest mutation is in chromosome 16.

Risk factors for progressive renal disease:

  • Male gender
  • kidney size
  • earlier onset of symptoms
  • proteinuria
  • High urinary sodium excretion
  • hypertension - patients with larger kidneys tend to have hypertension.
  • haematuria was not mentioned

PKD 1:

  • Earlier presentation with symptoms
  • More cysts
  • Larger kidneys
  • Earlier onset of CK

Clinical detection

The diagnosis is most commonly made in the settings of

  • routine evaluation in an asymptomatic patient with a positive family history of ADPKD,
  • initial work-up for new-onset hypertension,
  • as an incidental finding during an imaging study performed for an unrelated reason (eg, pregnancy, trauma, spinal pain),
  • and during evaluation of ADPKD-specific symptoms (hematuria, cyst rupture, pyelonephritis, kidney stones, etc).

Presenting complaints:

  • commonest - flank pain due to come colocation of PKD
  • hypertension
    • Hypertension is very common by 30-40 years. (Even when renal function is normal)
  • hematuria,
  • proteinuria,
  • kidney function impairment.

Diagnosis is primarily by imaging. (Genetic testing usually not required).
All patients will develop renal cysts.

Imaging Criteria overview:
For patients who have a family history
For young adults, > total of 3 cysts
For older adults(40 y/o and above), > 2 cysts in each kidney.
For patients without a family history, there are no well defined imaging diagnostic criteria.
Cut-off of 10 or more cysts per kidney is reasonable.

Extra renal manifestations

  • Cerebral vasculature aneurysms
    • rupture causing SAH is the most dangerous complication of PKD.
    • one in 10 patients with PKD have intracranial aneurysms.
    • doubly dangerous becuase these patients also have hypertension!
    • screening for aneurysm is not done routinely. (Recommended in some situations such as when patient has a high risk job); CT angiography is used for screen I
  • Hepatic and pancreatic cysts
    • hepatic cysts usually only cause pain when the become large enough.
  • Valvular dysfunction - MR and AR + coronary aneurysms
  • Colonic diverticulae
  • Seminal vesicle cysts

Angina

Overview of management of Angina

We're talking about "Chronic coronary syndrome" = "Stable ischemic heart disease".
Angina equivalents = dyspnoea on exertion, + others. #TODO

Goals of care:

  • relieve symptoms -> [[#antianginal medications]]
  • Preventing disease progression
    • Medication - aspirin
    • Risk factor management - lipid lowering therapy, smoking cessation, BP control, weight loss, optimal DM management, regular exercise, stress reduction etc.
  • Prevent future cardiac events (like ACS, death)

Place for angiography and revascularization:

  • patient has symptoms that interfere with everyday functioning despite maximum medical therapy
  • Non-invasive testing suggests that a large amount of viable myocardium is at risk.

Antianginal medications

3 main classes of medications

  1. Beta blockers - see [[#Beta blockers]] below
    1. First line anti anginal medications; Initial step in angina management is "beta blocker montherapy." Beta blockers are the only antianginals proven to reduced reinfarction and reduce mortablity.
    2. All are equally effective.
    3. Mechanism: reduce heart rate and contractility -> reduced oxygen demand -> therefore delay the onset of angina during exercise. Also reduced LV wall stressby their antihypertensive action.
    4. Beta blockers reduce mortality when it comes to secondary prevention but technically, there is no evidence that they prevent the first MI in a patient with angina.
    5. Contraindicated in prinz-metal angina; unopposed alpha action may exacerbate coronary vasospasm.
  2. CCBs
    1. Can use as monotherapy when beta blockers are contraindicated.
    2. or as combination with beta blockers.
    3. contraindicated in LV dysfunction.
    4. diltiazem and verapamil (nondihyropyridine) or amlopidine are preferred.
    5. Mechanism: Coronary and peripheral vasodilation and reduced contractility.
  3. Long acting nitrates
    1. Used as mono therapy or combination with beta blockers.
    2. Tolerance is a problem for long term therapy. (due to decreased vascular sensitivity to nitrates)
    3. Mechanism: They dilate systemic arteries, systemic veins and coronary arteries. Venodilation >> arterial dilation. (increased bioavailability to venous smooth muscle) Therefore, the main antianginal effect is due to venodilation -> reduced preload -> reduced ventricular wall stress -> reduced oxygen deman -> antianginal effect.
  4. Newer addition - ranolazine - late sodium channel blocker.

Note: Ivabradine, despite being a heart rate lowering drug is NOT given as an antianginal.

Combination therapy is commonplace for antianginal medication.

Beta blocker pharmacology

There are 3 types of beta receptors.
B1 - heart
B2 - lungs
B3 - adipose tissue

Cardioselective beta blockers are B1 selective. Non selective blockers block both. Selective blockers may block B2 at high doses.
Cardioselective - Bisoprolol, atenolol, Metoprolol + esmolol, bisoprolol.
Alpha-adrenergic blocking activity - lebetalol and carvedilol block beta and alpha receptors. They reduce coronary and peripheral vascular resistance.

All beta blockers appear equally effective in the treatment of stable angina.

Two groups of beta blockers based on metabolism

Eliminated by hepatic metabolism Eliminated unchanged by kidney
Lipid soluble water soluble
High CNS penetration (more SE) poor CNS penetration
short half lives longer half lives
variable bioavailability less variable
completely absorbed in small intestine incompletely absorbed by the gut
propranolol and metoprolol Atenolol, sotalol

hepatic - Metoprolol and propronolol
SAK - Sotalol and atenolol - Kidney

Goodpasture's syndrome

#2022SBR Q6

[!WARNING] Importance of quick diagnosis
Quick diagnosis makes for a better outcome as delay leads to renal damage which in turn leads to low chance of renal recovery. .

Background / context

Immune complex mediated, small vessel vasculitis.
Prototype disease of "diffuse alveolar haemorrhage syndromes".

  • These can be either with pathologic capillaritis or without ->[[diffuseAlveolarHaemorrhageSyndromes.png]] Source
  • Diffuse alveolar haemorrhage syndromes consist of a triad of haemoptysis, anaemia and diffuse pulmonary infiltrates.

Pathogenesis / pathology of goodpasture's syndrome

Goodpasture's syndrome has a triad of features:

  1. Circulating antibodies against intrinsic antigen of basement membranes of lung and kidney. Same antigen is expressed in the lung and the kidney.
  2. Pulmonary haemorrhage
  3. Glomerulonephritis - proliferative, rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis with crescent formation
  • Lung Histology: focal necrosis of alveolar walls associated with intra-alveolar haemorrhages. Macrophages will contain haemosiderin, engulfed from previous episodes.
  • Histology : kidney - characteristic linear pattern of immunoglobulin deposition.

Clinical presentation of Goodpasture's syndrome

Two age peaks : 30 years -> more likely to present with pulmonary haemorrhage;
> 50 years : more likely to present with isolated glomerulonephritis.

>90% present with features of RPGN; (hematuria, proteinuria, cellular casts, kidney function impairment). A large percentage have simultaneous pumonary haemorrhage. A few present with isolated pulmonary haemorrhage. Prodrome of systemic symptoms is short.

[!INFO] Nephritic sediment
nephritic sediment is characterized by dysmorphic red cells (including acanthocytes), white cells, and red cell and granular casts.
? AKA active sediment

Respiratory symptoms may precede glomerulonephritis by weeks to months.
Mild to life threatening haemopsytis.

Carbon monoxide gas transfer is increased (increased blood in the alveoli [[Respiratory medicine MCQ discussion#Mechanism of DLCO]])

Diagnosis : serum for anti-GBM antibodies and renal biopsy.
Treatment: remove the antibodies by plasmapheresis and prevent recurrent with immunosuppression (prednisilon / cyclophosphamide)
Prognosis: Recurrence is rare; earlier diagnosis -> less severe renal failure -> recovery; late diagnosis or significant renal impairment at presentation -> chronic kidney disease and dialysis requirement.

Urinalysis

Source

Casts


Represents protein precipitated in the distal convoluted tubules.
Composed of Tamm-Horsfall protein which is made by the renal tubular epithelium.

  • Hyaline casts - only tamm horsfall protein; least significant type of cast.
  • Granular casts - consist of cell debris, plasma proteins (fibrinogen, immune complexes). Seen in
    • Course, deeply pigmented, muddy brown casts are considered characteristic of ATN. a
    • Pyelonephritis
    • Glomerulonephritis
    • Malignant nephrosclerosis
    • Presence of red cells in the case => Glomerular injury.
  • Fatty casts / urinary lipids (cholesterol esters) : nephrotic syndrome, mercury poisoning, ethylene glycol poisoning.
  • RBC casts - Hallmark of glomerulonephritis; esp. proliferative glomerulonephritis.
  • WBC casts - interstitial nephritis, pyelonephritis.
  • Tubular epithelial cell casts : ATN, acute interstitial nephritis, proliferative glomerulonephritis.

Cells in the urine

Normal looking RBCs can be seen in any cause of macroscopic or microscopic haematuria.
Dysmorphic RBCs are suggestive of glomerular disease. (esp. acanthocytse - specificity of 98% for glomerulonephritis). RBC casts also suggest glomerulonephritis.

WBCs - usually associated with bacterial infection; also nephrolithiasis / interstitial nephritis.

Antiepileptic medications

Mechanisms of action

For some drugs, precise mechanism is unknown or several mechanisms are suspected.

See table in up to date

Alteration of sodium currents is the most common mechanism of action of available antiseizure medications.

Type of receptor blockade may explain why some drugs are more effective for particular types of seizures.

Phenytoin , phenobarbitone and carbamazepine are some of the oldest antiseizure medications. - Newer drugs have better pharmacokinetics.

Carbamazepine

Binds Na Channels

This binding extends the inactivated phase and inhibits the generation of rapid action potentials when the cell is experiencing incoming depolarizing trains

Phenytoin and fosphenytoin

#2023SBR Q23

Fosphenytoin is the prodrug. Superceded Phenytoin for IV use. (? Not really in SL)
Block Na channels, like carbamazepine.
Inhibits synaptic transmission.
And others...

seizure types

focal and generalized seizures
for status epilepticus
and as a second-line agent for patients with mixed seizures

Pharmacology of Phenytoin

95% protein bound ; renal failure impairs protein binding.
Valproate is another highly protein bound drug which ?may displace Phenytoin and increase its plasma levels.

potent, broad spectrum CYP and glucuronidation inducer.

Side effects:
Systemic: gingival hypertrophy, body hair increase, rash, folic acid depletion, reduced bone density (enzyme induction -> incr. Vitamin D catabolism)

Stevens-Johnson / TEN (commoner in south Asia!)

[!INFO] Ataxia
"ataxia" - disordered

Neurologic :
confusion
Slurred speech, ataxia, diplopia (all involving the head region)
Neuropathy

Phenobarbital

Binds GABA-A receptor, potentiates GAABA action, causing hyper polarization and increased neuronal stability.

potent, broad spectrum CYP and glucuronidation inducer.

Side effects:
Commonest side effect: sedation, reduced concentration, and mood changes including depression

Teratogenicity with #pregnancy is another risk, with a relatively high rate of major malformations in fetuses exposed to phenobarbital.

Chronic use is associate with an increased risk of decreased bone density, Dupuytren contractures, plantar fibromatosis, and frozen shoulder.
